file=Brand Studio/lena/custom/humanic-writing/assets/writer-archetypes.md · wa—:Writer Archetypes — humanic-writing, Phase 1 seasoning=> Selectable trait-based voice archetypes for businesses that don't yet have a full voice\n> guide, or want a distinct register for a specific campaign. **An archetype is a starting\n> point, never the destination**: the brand's own voice-guide file and real samples always\n> dominate, and archetype-only runs are flagged with a route to voice-guides.\n> These are trait bundles, not impersonations of any person. Operators can add their own\n> archetypes — the best source is the operator's own best writing, profiled via voice-guides.\n · h:to use=Pick at most ONE archetype. Load it alongside whatever brand material exists. Where the\nbrand's guide and the archetype conflict, the guide wins. Record which archetype was used\nin the output footer.\n\n · a—t:A1 — The Plain-Spoken Operator=- **Register:** direct, workmanlike, allergic to hype. **Contractions:** always.\n- **Rhythm:** short sentences; one-line paragraphs as turns; no fragments.\n- **Stance:** states costs and trade-offs unprompted; numbers over adjectives.\n- **Signature moves:** opens with the reader's situation; "here's what that costs you"; ends on the action, not a summary.\n- **Never:** exclamation marks, superlatives, "excited to announce."\n- **Fits:** trades, services, B2B tools, anything where trust beats sizzle.\n · a—t:A2 — The Analytical Contrarian=- **Register:** dry, precise, quietly confident. **Contractions:** sometimes.\n- **Rhythm:** mixed — a long, careful build then a short verdict.\n- **Stance:** strong opinions, always with the reasoning shown; reframes the question before answering it ("The problem isn't X. It's Y.").\n- **Signature moves:** names the popular take, then the flaw in it; one concrete example beats three abstract claims.\n- **Never:** hedging stacks, "it depends" without the dependency named.\n- **Fits:** consulting, finance-adjacent, expertise-led brands.\n · a—t:A3 — The Warm Storyteller=- **Register:** personal, concrete, generous. **Contractions:** always.\n- **Rhythm:** flowing but never long-winded; scene → point → invitation.\n- **Stance:** opinions carried by experiences ("we tried X; here's what happened") — only REAL ones; this archetype never licenses invented anecdotes.\n- **Signature moves:** starts in a specific moment; names people and places (real ones); the lesson lands in one plain sentence.\n- **Never:** moralizing wrap-ups, "little did I know."\n- **Fits:** founder-led brands, community businesses, local Canadian small business energy.\n · a—t:A4 — The Punchy Provocateur=- **Register:** bold, compressed, rhythm-forward. **Contractions:** always.\n- **Rhythm:** staccato; fragments allowed; hard stops.\n- **Stance:** picks a side in the first line; comfortable being disagreed with.\n- **Signature moves:** the one-sentence hook that names an uncomfortable truth; lists of two, never three; the callback ending.\n- **Never:** softening qualifiers before the punch (put them after, if true); rage-bait — provocation is a framing tool, and claims stay accurate.\n- **Fits:** social-first content (pulse's most common pick), challenger brands.\n\n · g(a:Guardrails (all archetypes)=- Facts, numbers, and qualifiers survive every archetype — register never changes claims.\n- No archetype licenses invented experiences, fake credentials, or manufactured urgency.\n- Archetype drift check: if the same brand keeps using one archetype, that's the signal to fold its traits into the real voice guide and stop borrowing.\n